 particular, it discusses how international relationships provide opportunities to create and pursue ideals, and why they are essential for the well-being of political communities. It argues that state actors project the idea of ‘good’ onto idealised, distant objects, in order to restore a sense of the ‘good state’.The book makes a distinctive and original contribution to debates about the role of ethics in international relations, and will be of particular interest to academics, policy-makers and students of international relations, Africa and British foreign policy, as well as anyone interested in ethics in international affairs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aInternational Relations 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aBritain.  aNew Labour.  aSierra Leone.  aTony Blair.  adebt relief.  aforeign policy.  ainternational relations.  amilitary intervention.  apolitical communities.1 aGallagher, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779422240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794222/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles